# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: auxotrophy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] The **Ames test** is a widely employed method that uses bacteria to test whether a given chemical can cause mutations in the DNA of the test organism.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] More formally, it is a biological assay to assess the mutagenic potential of chemical compounds.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] A positive test indicates that the chemical is mutagenic and therefore may act as a carcinogen, because cancer is often linked to mutation.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] The test serves as a quick and convenient assay to estimate the carcinogenic potential of a compound because standard carcinogen assays on mice and rats are time-consuming (taking two to three years to complete) and expensive.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] However, false-positives and false-negatives are known.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] The procedure was described in a series of papers in the early 1970s by Bruce Ames and his group at the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] The Ames test uses several strains of the bacterium *Salmonella typhimurium* that carry mutations in genes involved in histidine biosynthesis.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] These strains are auxotrophic mutants, i.e. they require histidine for growth, but cannot produce it.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] The method tests the capability of the tested substance in creating mutations that result in a return to a "prototrophic" state, so that the cells can grow on a histidine-free medium.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] The tester strains are specially constructed to detect either frameshift (e.g. strains TA-1537 and TA-1538) or point (e.g. strain TA-1531) mutations in the genes required to synthesize histidine, so that mutagens acting via different mechanisms may be identified.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] Some compounds are quite specific, causing reversions in just one or two strains.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] The tester strains also carry mutations in the genes responsible for lipopolysaccharide synthesis, making the cell wall of the bacteria more permeable, and in the excision repair system to make the test more sensitive.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] Larger organisms like mammals have metabolic processes that could potentially turn a chemical considered not mutagenic into one that is or one that is considered mutagenic into one that is not.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] Therefore, to more effectively test a chemical compound's mutagenicity in relation to larger organisms, rat liver enzymes can be added in an attempt to replicate the metabolic processes' effect on the compound being tested in the Ames Test.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] Rat liver extract is optionally added to simulate the effect of metabolism, as some compounds, like benzo[*a*]pyrene, are not mutagenic themselves but their metabolic products are.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] The bacteria are spread on an agar plate with a small amount of histidine.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] This small amount of histidine in the growth medium allows the bacteria to grow for an initial time and have the opportunity to mutate.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] When the histidine is depleted only bacteria that have mutated to gain the ability to produce its own histidine will survive.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] The mutagenicity of a substance is proportional to the number of colonies observed.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] Mutagens identified via Ames test are also possible carcinogens, and early studies by Ames showed that 90% of known carcinogens may be identified via this test.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] Later studies however showed identification of 50–70% of known carcinogens.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] The test was used to identify a number of compounds previously used in commercial products as potential carcinogens.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] Examples include tris(2,3-dibromopropyl)phosphate, which was used as a flame retardant in plastic and textiles such as children's sleepwear, and furylfuramide which was used as an antibacterial additive in food in Japan in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] Furylfuramide in fact had previously passed animal tests, but more vigorous tests after its identification in the Ames test showed it to be carcinogenic.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] Their positive tests resulted in those chemicals being withdrawn from use in consumer products.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] One interesting result from the Ames test is that the dose response curve using varying concentrations of the chemical is almost always linear, indicating that there is no threshold concentration for mutagenesis.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] It therefore suggests that, as with radiation, there may be no safe threshold for chemical mutagens or carcinogens.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] However, some have proposed that organisms could tolerate low levels of mutagens due to protective mechanisms such as DNA repair, and thus a threshold may exist for certain chemical mutagens.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] He also cautioned against the "hysteria over tiny traces of chemicals that may or may not cause cancer", that "completely drives out the major risks you should be aware of".
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] The Ames test is often used as one of the initial screens for potential drugs to weed out possible carcinogens, and it is one of the eight tests required under the Pesticide Act (USA) and one of the six tests required under the Toxic Substances Control Act (USA).
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] Mutagens identified in the Ames test need not necessarily be carcinogenic, and further tests are required for any potential carcinogen identified in the test.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] Drugs that contain the nitrate moiety sometimes come back positive for Ames when they are indeed safe.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] The nitrate compounds may generate nitric oxide, an important signal molecule that can give a false positive.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] Nitroglycerin is an example that gives a positive Ames yet is still used in treatment today.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] Nitrates in food however may be reduced by bacterial action to nitrites which are known to generate carcinogens by reacting with amines and amides.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] Long toxicology and outcome studies are needed with such compounds to disprove a positive Ames test.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] The Ames test was initially developed using agar plates (the plate incorporation technique), as described above.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] Since that time, an alternative to performing the Ames test has been developed, which is known as the "fluctuation method".
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] This technique is the same in concept as the agar-based method, with bacteria being added to a reaction mixture with a small amount of histidine, which allows the bacteria to grow and mutate, returning to synthesize their own histidine.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] By including a pH indicator, the frequency of mutation is counted in microplates as the number of wells which have changed color (caused by a drop in pH due to metabolic processes of reproducing bacteria).
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] As with the traditional Ames test, the sample is compared to the natural background rate of reverse mutation in order to establish the genotoxicity of a substance.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] The fluctuation method is performed entirely in liquid culture and is scored by counting the number of wells that turn yellow from purple in 96-well or 384-well microplates.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] In the 96-well plate method the frequency of mutation is counted as the number of wells out of 96 which have changed color.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] In the more scaled-down 384-well plate microfluctuation method the frequency of mutation is counted as the number of wells out of 48 which have changed color after 2 days of incubation.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] A test sample is assayed across 6 dose levels with concurrent zero-dose (background) and positive controls which all fit into one 384-well plate.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] The assay is performed in triplicates to provide statistical robustness.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] It uses the recommended OECD Guideline 471 tester strains (histidine auxotrophs and tryptophan auxotrophs).
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] Most kits have consumable components in a ready-to-use state, including lyophilized bacteria, and tests can be performed using multichannel pipettes.
[src:auxotrophy/ames-test] The fluctuation method also allows for testing higher volumes of aqueous samples (up to 75% v/v), increasing the sensitivity and extending its application to low-level environmental mutagens.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Amino acids can be classified according to the locations of the core structural functional groups (alpha- (α-), beta- (β-), gamma- (γ-) amino acids, etc.); other categories relate to polarity, ionization, and side-chain group type (aliphatic, acyclic, aromatic, polar, etc.).
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] In the form of proteins, amino-acid *residues* form the second-largest component (water being the largest) of human muscles and other tissues.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Beyond their role as residues in proteins, amino acids participate in a number of processes such as neurotransmitter transport and biosynthesis.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] It is thought that they played a key role in enabling life on Earth and its emergence.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Amino acids are formally named by the IUPAC-IUBMB Joint Commission on Biochemical Nomenclature in terms of the fictitious "neutral" structure shown in the illustration.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] For example, the systematic name of alanine is 2-aminopropanoic acid, based on the formula CH3−CH(NH2)−COOH.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] The first few amino acids were discovered in the early 1800s.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] In 1806, French chemists Louis-Nicolas Vauquelin and Pierre Jean Robiquet isolated a compound from asparagus that was subsequently named asparagine, the first amino acid to be discovered.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Cystine was discovered in 1810, although its monomer, cysteine, remained undiscovered until 1884.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Glycine and leucine were discovered in 1820.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] The last of the 20 common amino acids to be discovered was threonine in 1935 by William Cumming Rose, who also determined the essential amino acids and established the minimum daily requirements of all amino acids for optimal growth.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] The unity of the chemical category was recognized by Wurtz in 1865, but he gave no particular name to it.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] The first use of the term "amino acid" in the English language dates from 1898, while the German term, *Aminosäure*, was used earlier.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Proteins were found to yield amino acids after enzymatic digestion or acid hydrolysis.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] In 1902, Emil Fischer and Franz Hofmeister independently proposed that proteins are formed from many amino acids, whereby bonds are formed between the amino group of one amino acid with the carboxyl group of another, resulting in a linear structure that Fischer termed "peptide".
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] 2-, alpha-, or α-amino acids have the generic formula H2NCHRCOOH in most cases, where R is an organic substituent known as a "side chain".
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Of the many hundreds of described amino acids, 22 are proteinogenic ("protein-building").
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] It is these 22 compounds that combine to give a vast array of peptides and proteins assembled by ribosomes.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Non-proteinogenic amino acids may arise through nonribosomal peptide synthesis.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Modified amino acids, by contrast, typically result from post-translational modification.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Amino acids with the structure NH+3−CXY−CXY−CO−2, such as β-alanine, a component of carnosine and a few other peptides, are β-amino acids.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Ones with the structure NH+3−CXY−CXY−CXY−CO−2 are γ-amino acids, and so on, where X and Y are two substituents (one of which is normally H).
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] The carbon atom next to the carboxyl group is called the α–carbon.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] In proteinogenic amino acids, it bears the amine and the R group or side chain specific to each amino acid, as well as a hydrogen atom.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] With the exception of glycine, for which the side chain is also a hydrogen atom, the α–carbon is stereogenic.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] All chiral proteinogenic amino acids have the L configuration.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] They are "left-handed" enantiomers, which refers to the stereoisomers of the alpha carbon.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] A few D-amino acids ("right-handed") have been found in nature, e.g., in bacterial envelopes, as a neuromodulator (D-serine), and in some antibiotics.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Rarely, D-amino acid residues are found in proteins, and are converted from the L-amino acid as a post-translational modification.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Five amino acids possess a charge at neutral pH.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Often these side chains appear at the surfaces on proteins to enable their solubility in water, and side chains with opposite charges form important electrostatic contacts called salt bridges that maintain structures within a single protein or between interfacing proteins.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Many proteins bind metal into their structures specifically, and these interactions are commonly mediated by charged side chains such as aspartate, glutamate and histidine.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Under certain conditions, each ion-forming group can be charged, forming double salts.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] The two negatively charged amino acids at neutral pH are aspartate (Asp, D) and glutamate (Glu, E).
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] The anionic carboxylate groups behave as Brønsted bases in most circumstances.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Enzymes in very low pH environments, like the aspartic protease pepsin in mammalian stomachs, may have catalytic aspartate or glutamate residues that act as Brønsted acids.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] There are three amino acids with side chains that are cations at neutral pH: arginine (Arg, R), lysine (Lys, K) and histidine (His, H).
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Arginine has a charged guanidino group and lysine a charged alkyl amino group, and are fully protonated at pH 7.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Histidine's imidazole group has a pKa of 6.0, and is only around 10% protonated at neutral pH.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Because histidine is easily found in its basic and conjugate acid forms it often participates in catalytic proton transfers in enzyme reactions.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] The polar, uncharged amino acids serine (Ser, S), threonine (Thr, T), asparagine (Asn, N) and glutamine (Gln, Q) readily form hydrogen bonds with water and other amino acids.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] They do not ionize in normal conditions, a prominent exception being the catalytic serine in serine proteases.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] This is an example of severe perturbation, and is not characteristic of serine residues in general.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Threonine has two chiral centers, not only the L (2*S*) chiral center at the α-carbon shared by all amino acids apart from achiral glycine, but also (3*R*) at the β-carbon.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] The full stereochemical specification is (2*S*,3*R*)-L-threonine.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Because of the presence of phenolic hydroxyl group with a pKa = ~10, tyrosine is best classified as a neutral polar amino acid, but with amphipathic character that makes it less polar than classical small polar amino acid residues.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Nonpolar amino acid interactions are the primary driving force behind the processes that fold proteins into their functional three dimensional structures.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] None of these amino acids' side chains ionize easily, and therefore do not have pKas.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Several side chains are not described well by the charged, polar and hydrophobic categories.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Glycine (Gly, G) could be considered a polar amino acid since its small size means that its solubility is largely determined by the amino and carboxylate groups.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] However, the lack of any side chain provides glycine with a unique flexibility among amino acids with large ramifications to protein folding.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Cysteine (Cys, C) can also form hydrogen bonds readily, which would place it in the polar amino acid category, though it can often be found in protein structures forming covalent bonds, called disulphide bonds, with other cysteines.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] These bonds influence the folding and stability of proteins, and are essential in the formation of antibodies.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Proline (Pro, P) has an alkyl side chain and could be considered hydrophobic, but because the side chain joins back onto the alpha amino group it becomes particularly inflexible when incorporated into proteins.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Similar to glycine this influences protein structure in a way unique among amino acids.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Selenocysteine (Sec, U) is a rare amino acid not directly encoded by DNA, but is incorporated into proteins via the ribosome.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Selenocysteine has a lower redox potential compared to the similar cysteine, and participates in several unique enzymatic reactions.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Pyrrolysine (Pyl, O) is another amino acid not encoded in DNA, but synthesized into protein by ribosomes.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] It is found in archaeal species where it participates in the catalytic activity of several methyltransferases.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] The 20 canonical amino acids can be classified according to their properties.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Important factors are charge, hydrophilicity or hydrophobicity, size, and functional groups.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] These properties influence protein structure and protein–protein interactions.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] The water-soluble proteins tend to have their hydrophobic residues (Leu, Ile, Val, Phe, and Trp) buried in the middle of the protein, whereas hydrophilic side chains are exposed to the aqueous solvent.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] (In biochemistry, a residue refers to a specific monomer *within* the polymeric chain of a polysaccharide, protein or nucleic acid.) The integral membrane proteins tend to have outer rings of exposed hydrophobic amino acids that anchor them in the lipid bilayer.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Some peripheral membrane proteins have a patch of hydrophobic amino acids on their surface that sticks to the membrane.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] In a similar fashion, proteins that have to bind to positively charged molecules have surfaces rich in negatively charged amino acids such as glutamate and aspartate, while proteins binding to negatively charged molecules have surfaces rich in positively charged amino acids like lysine and arginine.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] For example, lysine and arginine are present in large amounts in the low-complexity regions of nucleic-acid binding proteins.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] There are various hydrophobicity scales of amino acid residues.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Some amino acids have special properties.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Cysteine can form covalent disulfide bonds to other cysteine residues.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Proline forms a cycle to the polypeptide backbone, and glycine is more flexible than other amino acids.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Glycine and proline are strongly present within low complexity regions of both eukaryotic and prokaryotic proteins, whereas the opposite is the case with cysteine, phenylalanine, tryptophan, methionine, valine, leucine, isoleucine, which are highly reactive, or complex, or hydrophobic.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] For example, a signaling protein can attach and then detach from a cell membrane, because it contains cysteine residues that can have the fatty acid palmitic acid added to them and subsequently removed.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] The common natural forms of amino acids have a zwitterionic structure, with −NH+3 (−NH+2− in the case of proline) and −CO−2 functional groups attached to the same C atom, and are thus α-amino acids, and are the only ones found in proteins during translation in the ribosome.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] In aqueous solution at pH close to neutrality, amino acids are energetically favored in their zwitterionic form, with a deprotonated CO−2 group and a protonated NH+3 group, because the high dielectric constant of water and its hydrogen-bonding network effectively stabilize separated charges.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Thus, the overall structure is NH+3−CHR−CO−2, and the so-called "neutral forms" −NH2−CHR−CO2H are not present to any measurable degree at physiological pH.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] In strongly acidic conditions (pH below 3), the carboxylate group becomes protonated and the structure becomes an ammonio carboxylic acid, NH+3−CHR−CO2H.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] This is relevant for enzymes like pepsin that are active in acidic environments such as the mammalian stomach and lysosomes, but does not significantly apply to intracellular enzymes.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] In highly basic conditions (pH greater than 10, not normally seen in physiological conditions), the ammonio group is deprotonated to give NH2−CHR−CO−2.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Although various definitions of acids and bases are used in chemistry, the only one that is useful for chemistry in aqueous solution is that of Brønsted: an acid is a species that can donate a proton to another species, and a base is one that can accept a proton.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] This criterion is used to label the groups in the above illustration.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] The carboxylate side chains of aspartate and glutamate residues are the principal Brønsted bases in proteins.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Likewise, lysine, tyrosine and cysteine will typically act as a Brønsted acid.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Histidine under these conditions can act both as a Brønsted acid and a base.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] For amino acids with uncharged side-chains the zwitterion predominates at pH values between the two p*K*a values, but coexists in equilibrium with small amounts of net negative and net positive ions.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] At the midpoint between the two p*K*a values, the trace amount of net negative and trace of net positive ions balance, so that average net charge of all forms present is zero.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] This pH is known as the isoelectric point p*I*, so p*I* = ⁠1/2⁠(p*K*a1 + p*K*a2).
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] For amino acids with charged side chains, the p*K*a of the side chain is involved.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Thus for aspartate or glutamate with negative side chains, the terminal amino group is essentially entirely in the charged form −NH+3, but this positive charge needs to be balanced by the state with just one C-terminal carboxylate group is negatively charged.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] This occurs halfway between the two carboxylate p*K*a values: p*I* = ⁠1/2⁠(p*K*a1 + p*K*a(R)), where p*K*a(R) is the side chain p*K*a.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Similar considerations apply to other amino acids with ionizable side-chains, including not only glutamate (similar to aspartate), but also cysteine, histidine, lysine, tyrosine and arginine with positive side chains.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Amino acids have zero mobility in electrophoresis at their isoelectric point, although this behaviour is more usually exploited for peptides and proteins than single amino acids.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Zwitterionic amino acids exhibit minimal solubility at their isoelectric point, and in some cases can be isolated from aqueous solution by adjusting the pH to the appropriate isoelectric value.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Although one-letter symbols are included in the table, IUPAC–IUBMB recommend that "Use of the one-letter symbols should be restricted to the comparison of long sequences".
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] In addition to the specific amino acid codes, placeholders are used in cases where chemical or crystallographic analysis of a peptide or protein cannot conclusively determine the identity of a residue.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] They are also used to summarize conserved protein sequence motifs.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] The use of single letters to indicate sets of similar residues is similar to the use of abbreviation codes for degenerate bases.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] In addition, many nonstandard amino acids have a specific code.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] For example, several peptide drugs, such as Bortezomib and MG132, are artificially synthesized and retain their protecting groups, which have specific codes.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Bortezomib is Pyz–Phe–boroLeu, and MG132 is Z–Leu–Leu–Leu–al.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] To aid in the analysis of protein structure, photo-reactive amino acid analogs are available.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] These include photoleucine (**pLeu**) and photomethionine (**pMet**).
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Amino acids are the precursors to proteins.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] They join by condensation reactions to form short polymer chains called peptides or longer chains called either polypeptides or proteins.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] These chains are linear and unbranched, with each amino acid residue within the chain attached to two neighboring amino acids.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] In nature, the process of making proteins encoded by RNA genetic material is called *translation* and involves the step-by-step addition of amino acids to a growing protein chain by a ribozyme that is called a ribosome.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] The order in which the amino acids are added is read through the genetic code from an mRNA template, which is an RNA derived from one of the organism's genes.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] There are 22 amino acids that get naturally incorporated into polypeptides; these are called *proteinogenic amino acids* or *natural amino acids*.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Of these, 20 are encoded by the universal genetic code.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] The remaining 2, selenocysteine and pyrrolysine, are incorporated into proteins by unique synthetic mechanisms.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Selenocysteine is incorporated when the mRNA being translated includes a SECIS element, which causes the UGA codon to encode selenocysteine instead of a stop codon.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Pyrrolysine is used by some methanogenic archaea in enzymes that they use to produce methane.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] It is coded for with the codon UAG, which is normally a stop codon in other organisms.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] The 20 amino acids that are encoded directly by the codons of the universal genetic code are called *standard* or *canonical* amino acids.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] A modified form of methionine (*N*-formylmethionine) is often incorporated in place of methionine as the initial amino acid of proteins in bacteria, mitochondria and plastids (including chloroplasts).
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Other amino acids are called *nonstandard* or *non-canonical*.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Most of the nonstandard amino acids are also non-proteinogenic (i.e. they cannot be incorporated into proteins during translation), but two of them are proteinogenic, as they can be incorporated translationally into proteins by exploiting information not encoded in the universal genetic code.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] The two nonstandard proteinogenic amino acids are selenocysteine (present in many non-eukaryotes as well as most eukaryotes, but not coded directly by DNA) and pyrrolysine (found only in some archaea and at least one bacterium).
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] The incorporation of these nonstandard amino acids is rare.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] For example, 25 human proteins include selenocysteine in their primary structure, and the structurally characterized enzymes (selenoenzymes) employ selenocysteine as the catalytic moiety in their active sites.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Pyrrolysine and selenocysteine are encoded via variant codons.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] For example, selenocysteine is encoded by stop codon and SECIS element.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Aside from the 22 proteinogenic amino acids, many *non-proteinogenic* amino acids are known.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] These either are not found in proteins (for example carnitine, GABA, ornithine) or are not produced directly and in isolation by standard cellular machinery.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] For example, hydroxyproline is synthesized from proline, and selenomethionine is produced by metabolic modification of methionine.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Non-proteinogenic amino acids that are found in proteins are formed by post-translational modification.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Such modifications can also determine the localization of the protein, e.g., the addition of long hydrophobic groups can cause a protein to bind to a phospholipid membrane.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Some non-proteinogenic amino acids are not found in proteins.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Examples include 2-aminoisobutyric acid and the neurotransmitter gamma-aminobutyric acid.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Non-proteinogenic amino acids often occur as intermediates in the metabolic pathways for standard amino acids – for example, ornithine and citrulline occur in the urea cycle, part of amino acid catabolism (see below).
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] A rare exception to the dominance of α-amino acids in biology is the β-amino acid beta alanine (3-aminopropanoic acid), which is used in plants and microorganisms in the synthesis of pantothenic acid (vitamin B5), a component of coenzyme A.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Many proteinogenic and non-proteinogenic amino acids have biological functions beyond being precursors to proteins and peptides.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] In humans, amino acids also have important roles in diverse biosynthetic pathways.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Defenses against herbivores in plants sometimes employ amino acids.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] However, not all of the functions of other abundant nonstandard amino acids are known.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Animals ingest amino acids in the form of protein.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] The protein is broken down into its constituent amino acids in the process of digestion.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] The amino acids are then used to synthesize new proteins and other nitrogenous biomolecules, or they are further catabolized through oxidation to provide a source of energy.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] The oxidation pathway starts with the removal of the amino group by a transaminase; the amino group is then fed into the urea cycle.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] The other product of transamidation is a keto acid that enters the citric acid cycle.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Glucogenic amino acids can also be converted into glucose, through gluconeogenesis.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Of the 20 standard amino acids, nine (His, Ile, Leu, Lys, Met, Phe, Thr, Trp and Val) are called essential amino acids because the human body cannot synthesize them from other compounds at the level needed for normal growth, so they must be obtained from food.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] In addition, cysteine, tyrosine, and arginine are considered semiessential amino acids, and taurine a semi-essential aminosulfonic acid in children.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Some amino acids are conditionally essential for certain ages or medical conditions.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Essential amino acids may also vary from species to species.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] The metabolic pathways that synthesize these monomers are not fully developed.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Amino acids are sometimes added to animal feed because some of the components of these feeds, such as soybeans, have low levels of some of the essential amino acids, especially of lysine, methionine, threonine, and tryptophan.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Likewise amino acids are used to chelate metal cations in order to improve the absorption of minerals from feed supplements.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] The food industry is a major consumer of amino acids, especially glutamic acid, which is used as a flavor enhancer, and aspartame (aspartylphenylalanine 1-methyl ester), which is used as an artificial sweetener.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Amino acids are sometimes added to food by manufacturers to alleviate symptoms of mineral deficiencies, such as anemia, by improving mineral absorption and reducing negative side effects from inorganic mineral supplementation.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Amino acids are low-cost feedstocks used in chiral pool synthesis as enantiomerically pure building blocks.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Amino acids are used in the synthesis of some cosmetics.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] The chelating ability of amino acids is sometimes used in fertilizers to facilitate the delivery of minerals to plants in order to correct mineral deficiencies, such as iron chlorosis.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] These fertilizers are also used to prevent deficiencies from occurring and to improve the overall health of the plants.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Amino acids have been considered as components of biodegradable polymers, which have applications as environmentally friendly packaging and in medicine in drug delivery and the construction of prosthetic implants.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] An interesting example of such materials is polyaspartate, a water-soluble biodegradable polymer that may have applications in disposable diapers and agriculture.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Due to its solubility and ability to chelate metal ions, polyaspartate is also being used as a biodegradable antiscaling agent and a corrosion inhibitor.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] The commercial production of amino acids usually relies on mutant bacteria that overproduce individual amino acids using glucose as a carbon source.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Some amino acids are produced by enzymatic conversions of synthetic intermediates.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] 2-Aminothiazoline-4-carboxylic acid is an intermediate in one industrial synthesis of L-cysteine for example.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Aspartic acid is produced by the addition of ammonia to fumarate using a lyase.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] In plants, nitrogen is first assimilated into organic compounds in the form of glutamate, formed from alpha-ketoglutarate and ammonia in the mitochondrion.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] For other amino acids, plants use transaminases to move the amino group from glutamate to another alpha-keto acid.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] For example, aspartate aminotransferase converts glutamate and oxaloacetate to alpha-ketoglutarate and aspartate.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Other organisms use transaminases for amino acid synthesis, too.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Nonstandard amino acids are usually formed through modifications to standard amino acids.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] For example, homocysteine is formed through the transsulfuration pathway or by the demethylation of methionine via the intermediate metabolite *S*-adenosylmethionine, while hydroxyproline is made by a post translational modification of proline.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Microorganisms and plants synthesize many uncommon amino acids.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] For example, some microbes make 2-aminoisobutyric acid and lanthionine, which is a sulfide-bridged derivative of alanine.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Both of these amino acids are found in peptidic lantibiotics such as alamethicin.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] However, in plants, 1-aminocyclopropane-1-carboxylic acid is a small disubstituted cyclic amino acid that is an intermediate in the production of the plant hormone ethylene.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] The formation of amino acids and peptides is assumed to have preceded and perhaps induced the emergence of life on earth.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Amino acids can form from simple precursors under various conditions.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Surface-based chemical metabolism of amino acids and very small compounds may have led to the build-up of amino acids, coenzymes and phosphate-based small carbon molecules.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Amino acids and similar building blocks could have been elaborated into proto-peptides, with peptides being considered key players in the origin of life.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] In the famous Urey-Miller experiment, the passage of an electric arc through a mixture of methane, hydrogen, and ammonia produces a large number of amino acids.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Several hypotheses invoke the Strecker synthesis whereby hydrogen cyanide, simple aldehydes, ammonia, and water produce amino acids.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] According to a review, amino acids, and even peptides, "turn up fairly regularly in the various experimental broths that have been allowed to be cooked from simple chemicals.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] This is because nucleotides are far more difficult to synthesize chemically than amino acids." For a chronological order, it suggests that there must have been a 'protein world' or at least a 'polypeptide world', possibly later followed by the 'RNA world' and the 'DNA world'.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Codon–amino acids mappings may be the biological information system at the primordial origin of life on Earth.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] While amino acids and consequently simple peptides must have formed under different experimentally probed geochemical scenarios, the transition from an abiotic world to the first life forms is to a large extent still unresolved.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Amino acids undergo the reactions expected of the constituent functional groups.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] As both the amine and carboxylic acid groups of amino acids can react to form amide bonds, one amino acid molecule can react with another and become joined through an amide linkage.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] This polymerization of amino acids is what creates proteins.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] This condensation reaction yields the newly formed peptide bond and a molecule of water.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] In cells, this reaction does not occur directly; instead, the amino acid is first activated by attachment to a transfer RNA molecule through an ester bond.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] This aminoacyl-tRNA is produced in an ATP-dependent reaction carried out by an aminoacyl tRNA synthetase.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] This aminoacyl-tRNA is then a substrate for the ribosome, which catalyzes the attack of the amino group of the elongating protein chain on the ester bond.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] As a result of this mechanism, all proteins made by ribosomes are synthesized starting at their *N*-terminus and moving toward their *C*-terminus.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] However, not all peptide bonds are formed in this way.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] In a few cases, peptides are synthesized by specific enzymes.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] For example, the tripeptide glutathione is an essential part of the defenses of cells against oxidative stress.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] This peptide is synthesized in two steps from free amino acids.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] In the first step, gamma-glutamylcysteine synthetase condenses cysteine and glutamate through a peptide bond formed between the side chain carboxyl of the glutamate (the gamma carbon of this side chain) and the amino group of the cysteine.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] This dipeptide is then condensed with glycine by glutathione synthetase to form glutathione.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] In chemistry, peptides are synthesized by a variety of reactions.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] One of the most-used in solid-phase peptide synthesis uses the aromatic oxime derivatives of amino acids as activated units.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] These are added in sequence onto the growing peptide chain, which is attached to a solid resin support.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Libraries of peptides are used in drug discovery through high-throughput screening.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] The combination of functional groups allow amino acids to be effective polydentate ligands for metal–amino acid chelates.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] The side chains of amino acids can also undergo posttranslational chemical reactions.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Degradation of an amino acid often begins with transamination, in which its amino group is transferred to α-ketoglutarate, forming glutamate.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] This process involves transaminases, often the same enzymes used in amino acid synthesis.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] In many vertebrates, the amino group is subsequently released as ammonia and converted to urea via the urea cycle for excretion.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] However, amino acid degradation can result in uric acid or ammonia instead, depending on the organism.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] For example, serine dehydratase converts serine directly to pyruvate and ammonia.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] Amino acids are bidentate ligands, forming transition metal amino acid complexes.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] The total nitrogen content of organic matter is mainly formed by the amino groups in proteins.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] The total Kjeldahl nitrogen (TKN) is a measure of nitrogen widely used in the analysis of (waste) water, soil, food, feed and organic matter in general.
[src:auxotrophy/amino-acid] As the name suggests, the Kjeldahl method is applied.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek was the language of Homer and of fifth-century Athenian historians, playwrights, and philosophers.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] It has contributed many words to English vocabulary and has been a standard subject of study in educational institutions of the Western world since the Renaissance.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] This article primarily contains information about the Epic and Classical periods of the language, which are the best-attested periods and considered most typical of Ancient Greek.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek comprised several dialects, such as Attic, Ionic, Doric, Aeolic, and Arcadocypriot; among them, Attic Greek became the basis of Koine Greek.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Just like Koine is often included in Ancient Greek, conversely, Mycenaean Greek is usually treated separately and not always included in Ancient Greek – reflecting the fact that Greek in the first millennium BC is considered prototypical of Ancient Greek.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek was a pluricentric language, divided into many dialects.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] The main dialect groups are Attic and Ionic, Aeolic, Arcadocypriot, and Doric, many of them with several subdivisions.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Some dialects are found in standardized literary forms in literature, while others are attested only in inscriptions.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] There are also several historical forms.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Homeric Greek is a literary form of Archaic Greek (derived primarily from Ionic and Aeolic) used in the epic poems, the *Iliad* and the *Odyssey*, and in later poems by other authors.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Homeric Greek had significant differences in grammar and pronunciation from Classical Attic and other Classical-era dialects.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] The origins, early form and development of the Hellenic language family are not well understood because of a lack of contemporaneous evidence.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Several theories exist about what Hellenic dialect groups may have existed between the divergence of early Greek-like speech from the common Proto-Indo-European language and the Classical period.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] They have the same general outline but differ in some of the detail.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] The only attested dialect from this period is Mycenaean Greek, but its relationship to the historical dialects and the historical circumstances of the times imply that the overall groups already existed in some form.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Scholars assume that major Ancient Greek period dialect groups developed no later than 1120 BC, at the time of the Dorian invasions—and that their first appearances as precise alphabetic writing began in the 8th century BC.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] The invasion would not be "Dorian" unless the invaders had some cultural relationship to the historical Dorians.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] The invasion is known to have displaced population to the later Attic-Ionic regions, who regarded themselves as descendants of the population displaced by or contending with the Dorians.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] The Greeks of this period believed there were three major divisions of all Greek people – Dorians, Aeolians, and Ionians (including Athenians), each with their own defining and distinctive dialects.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Allowing for their oversight of Arcadian, an obscure mountain dialect, and Cypriot, far from the center of Greek scholarship, this division of people and language is quite similar to the results of modern archaeological-linguistic investigation.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] (Southern Italy and Sicily) in the classical period.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] West vs. non-West Greek is the strongest-marked and earliest division, with non-West in subsets of Ionic-Attic (or Attic-Ionic) and Aeolic vs.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Arcadocypriot, or Aeolic and Arcado-Cypriot vs.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Arcadocypriot apparently descended more closely from the Mycenaean Greek of the Bronze Age.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Boeotian Greek had come under a strong Northwest Greek influence, and can in some respects be considered a transitional dialect, as exemplified in the poems of the Boeotian poet Pindar who wrote in Doric with a small Aeolic admixture.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Thessalian likewise had come under Northwest Greek influence, though to a lesser degree.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Pamphylian Greek, spoken in a small area on the southwestern coast of Anatolia and little preserved in inscriptions, may be either a fifth major dialect group, or it is Mycenaean Greek overlaid by Doric, with a non-Greek native influence.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Based on the conclusions drawn by several studies and findings such as Pella curse tablet, Emilio Crespo and most scholars suggest that ancient Macedonian was a Northwest Doric dialect, which shares isoglosses with its neighboring Thessalian dialects spoken in northeastern Thessaly.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Some have also suggested an Aeolic Greek classification.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] For example, fragments of the works of the poet Sappho from the island of Lesbos are in Aeolian.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Most of the dialect sub-groups listed above had further subdivisions, generally equivalent to a city-state and its surrounding territory, or to an island.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Doric notably had several intermediate divisions as well, into Island Doric (including Cretan Doric), Southern Peloponnesus Doric (including Laconian, the dialect of Sparta), and Northern Peloponnesus Doric (including Corinthian).
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] All the groups were represented by colonies beyond Greece proper as well, and these colonies generally developed local characteristics, often under the influence of settlers or neighbors speaking different Greek dialects.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] After the conquests of Alexander the Great in the late 4th century BC, a new international dialect known as Koine or Common Greek developed, largely based on Attic Greek, but with influence from other dialects.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] This dialect slowly replaced most of the older dialects, although the Doric dialect has survived in the Tsakonian language, which is spoken in the region of modern Sparta.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Doric has also passed down its aorist terminations into most verbs of Demotic Greek.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] By about the 6th century AD, the Koine had slowly metamorphosed into Medieval Greek.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Phrygian is an extinct Indo-European language of West and Central Anatolia, which is regarded by current consensus to have been closely related to Greek.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Among Indo-European branches with living descendants, Greek is often argued to have the closest genetic ties with Armenian (see also Graeco-Armenian) and Indo-Iranian languages (see Graeco-Aryan).
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek differs from Proto-Indo-European (PIE) and other Indo-European languages in certain ways.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] In phonotactics, ancient Greek words could end only in a vowel or /n s r/; final stops were lost, as in γάλα "milk", compared with γάλακτος "of milk" (genitive).
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] The pronunciation of Ancient Greek was very different from that of Modern Greek.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek had long and short vowels; many diphthongs; double and single consonants; voiced, voiceless, and aspirated stops; and a pitch accent.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] In Modern Greek, all vowels and consonants are short.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Many vowels and diphthongs once pronounced distinctly are pronounced as /i/ (iotacism).
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Some of the stops and glides in diphthongs have become fricatives, and the pitch accent has changed to a stress accent.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Many of the changes took place in the Koine Greek period.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] The writing system of Modern Greek, however, does not reflect all pronunciation changes.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] The examples below represent Attic Greek in the 5th century BC.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Ancient pronunciation cannot be reconstructed with certainty, but Greek from the period is well documented, and there is little disagreement among linguists as to the general nature of the sounds that the letters represent.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] /oː/ raised to [uː], probably by the 4th century BC.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Greek, like all of the older Indo-European languages, is highly inflected.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] It is highly archaic in its preservation of Proto-Indo-European forms.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] In ancient Greek, nouns (including proper nouns) have five cases (nominative, genitive, dative, accusative, and vocative), three genders (masculine, feminine, and neuter), and three numbers (singular, dual, and plural).
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Verbs have four moods (indicative, imperative, subjunctive, and optative) and three voices (active, middle, and passive), as well as three persons (first, second, and third) and various other forms.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Verbs are conjugated through seven combinations of tenses and aspect (generally simply called "tenses"): the present, future, and imperfect are imperfective in aspect; the aorist, present perfect, pluperfect and future perfect are perfective in aspect.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Most tenses display all four moods and three voices, although there is no future subjunctive or imperative.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Also, there is no imperfect subjunctive, optative or imperative.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] The infinitives and participles correspond to the finite combinations of tense, aspect, and voice.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] The indicative of past tenses adds (conceptually, at least) a prefix /e-/, called the augment.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] This was probably originally a separate word, meaning something like "then", added because tenses in PIE had primarily aspectual meaning.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] The augment is added to the indicative of the aorist, imperfect, and pluperfect, but not to any of the other forms of the aorist (no other forms of the imperfect and pluperfect exist).
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] The two kinds of augment in Greek are syllabic and quantitative.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] The syllabic augment is added to stems beginning with consonants, and simply prefixes *e* (stems beginning with *r*, however, add *er*).
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Some verbs augment irregularly; the most common variation is *e* → *ei*.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] The irregularity can be explained diachronically by the loss of *s* between vowels, or that of the letter *w*, which affected the augment when it was word-initial.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] In verbs with a preposition as a prefix, the augment is placed not at the start of the word, but between the preposition and the original verb.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] For example, προσ(-)βάλλω (I attack) goes to προσ**έ**βαλoν in the aorist.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] However compound verbs consisting of a prefix that is not a preposition retain the augment at the start of the word: αὐτο(-)μολῶ goes to **ηὐ**τομόλησα in the aorist.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Following Homer's practice, the augment is sometimes not made in poetry, especially epic poetry.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] The augment sometimes substitutes for reduplication; see below.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Almost all forms of the perfect, pluperfect, and future perfect reduplicate the initial syllable of the verb stem.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Irregular duplication can be understood diachronically.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] For example, *lambanō* (root *lab*) has the perfect stem *eilēpha* (not **lelēpha*) because it was originally *slambanō*, with perfect *seslēpha*, becoming *eilēpha* through compensatory lengthening.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Reduplication is also visible in the present tense stems of certain verbs.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] These stems add a syllable consisting of the root's initial consonant followed by *i*.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] A nasal stop appears after the reduplication in some verbs.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] The earliest extant examples of ancient Greek writing (c.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] 1450 BC) are in the syllabic script Linear B.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Beginning in the 8th century BC, however, the Greek alphabet became standard, albeit with some variation among dialects.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Early texts are written in boustrophedon style, but left-to-right became standard during the classic period.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Modern editions of ancient Greek texts are usually written with accents and breathing marks, interword spacing, modern punctuation, and sometimes mixed case, but these were all introduced later.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] The beginning of Apology by Plato exemplifies Attic Greek from the Classical period of ancient Greek.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] How you, men of Athens, are feeling under the power of my accusers, I do not know: actually, even I myself almost forgot who I was because of them, they spoke so persuasively.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] And yet, loosely speaking, nothing they have said is true.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] The study of Ancient Greek in European countries in addition to Latin occupied an important place in the syllabus from the Renaissance until the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] This was true as well in the United States, where many of the nation's founders received a classically based education.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Latin was emphasized in American colleges, but Greek also was required in the colonial and early national eras, and the study of ancient Greece became increasingly popular in the mid-to-late nineteenth century, the age of American philhellenism.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] In particular, female intellectuals of the era designated the mastering of ancient Greek as essential in becoming a "woman of letters".
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is still taught as a compulsory or optional subject especially at traditional or elite schools throughout Europe, such as public schools and grammar schools in the United Kingdom.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] In 2006/07, 15,000 pupils studied ancient Greek in Germany according to the Federal Statistical Office of Germany, and 280,000 pupils studied it in Italy.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] It is a compulsory subject alongside Latin in the humanities branch of the Spanish Baccalaureate.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is taught at most major universities worldwide, often combined with Latin as part of the study of classics.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] In 2010 it was offered in three primary schools in the UK, to boost children's language skills, and was one of seven foreign languages which primary schools could teach 2014 as part of a major drive to boost education standards.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is taught as a compulsory subject in all gymnasiums and lyceums in Greece.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] It appears to have ceased in 2010, having failed to gain the recognition and acceptance of teachers.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Its first issue appeared in April 2015 as an annex to *Hebdomada Aenigmatum*.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Alfred Rahlfs included a preface, a short history of the Septuagint text, and other front matter translated into ancient Greek in his 1935 edition of the Septuagint; Robert Hanhart also included the introductory remarks to the 2006 revised Rahlfs–Hanhart edition in the language as well.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] *Akropolis World News* reports weekly a summary of the most important news in ancient Greek.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is also used by organizations and individuals, mainly Greek, who wish to denote their respect, admiration or preference for the use of this language.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] This use is sometimes considered graphical, nationalistic or humorous.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] In any case, the fact that modern Greeks can still wholly or partly understand texts written in non-archaic forms of ancient Greek shows the affinity of the modern Greek language to its ancestral predecessor.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Ancient Greek is often used in the coinage of modern technical terms in the European languages: see English words of Greek origin.
[src:auxotrophy/ancient-greek-language] Latinized forms of ancient Greek roots are used in many of the scientific names of species and in scientific terminology.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] An **autotroph** is an organism that can convert abiotic sources of energy into energy stored in organic compounds, which can be used by other organisms.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] Autotrophs produce complex organic compounds (such as carbohydrates, fats, and proteins) using carbon from simple substances such as carbon dioxide, generally using energy from light or inorganic chemical reactions.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] Autotrophs do not need a living source of carbon or energy, and are the producers in a food chain, such as plants on land or algae in water.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] Autotrophs can reduce carbon dioxide to make organic compounds for biosynthesis and as stored chemical fuel.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] Most autotrophs use water as the reducing agent, but some can use other hydrogen compounds such as hydrogen sulfide.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] Autotrophs use a portion of the ATP produced during photosynthesis or the oxidation of chemical compounds to reduce NADP+ to NADPH to form organic compounds.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] Primary producers are at the lowest trophic level, and are the reasons why Earth sustains life to this day.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] Photoautotrophs convert the energy of light into chemical energy through photosynthesis, ultimately building organic molecules from carbon dioxide, an inorganic carbon source.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] Chemolithotrophs produce biomass from the oxidation of inorganic chemical compounds; they are frequently found in hydrothermal vents in the deep ocean and include some archaea and bacteria (unicellular organisms).
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] Most chemoautotrophs are lithotrophs, using inorganic electron donors such as hydrogen sulfide, hydrogen gas, elemental sulfur, ammonium, and ferrous oxide as reducing agents; and hydrogen sources for biosynthesis and chemical energy release.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] Chemolithoautotrophs are microorganisms that synthesize energy through the oxidation of inorganic compounds.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] They can sustain themselves entirely on atmospheric CO2 and inorganic chemicals without the need for light or organic compounds.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] They enzymatically catalyze redox reactions using mineral substrates to generate ATP energy.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] These substrates primarily include hydrogen, iron, nitrogen, and sulfur.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] Its ecological niche is often specialized to extreme environments, including deep marine hydrothermal vents, stratified sediment, and acidic hot springs.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] Some organisms rely on organic compounds as a source of carbon, but can use light or inorganic compounds as a source of energy.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] An organism that obtains carbon from organic compounds but obtains energy from light is called a *photoheterotroph*, while an organism that obtains carbon from organic compounds and energy from the oxidation of inorganic compounds is termed a *chemolithoheterotroph*.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] Evidence suggests that some fungi may also obtain energy from ionizing radiation: Such radiotrophic fungi were found growing inside a reactor of the Chernobyl nuclear power plant.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] The term *autotroph* was coined by the German botanist Albert Bernhard Frank in 1892.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] It stems from the ancient Greek word τροφή (*trophḗ*), meaning "nourishment" or "food".
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] Without primary producers, organisms that are capable of producing energy on their own, the biological systems of Earth would be unable to sustain themselves.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] Plants, along with other primary producers, produce the energy that other living beings consume, and the oxygen that they breathe.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] It is thought that the first organisms on Earth were primary producers located on the ocean floor.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] Autotrophs are fundamental to the food chains of all ecosystems in the world.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] They take energy from the environment in the form of sunlight or inorganic chemicals and use it to create fuel molecules such as carbohydrates.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] This mechanism is called primary production.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] Other organisms, called heterotrophs, take in autotrophs as food to carry out functions necessary for their life.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] Thus, heterotrophs – all animals, almost all fungi, and most bacteria and protozoa – depend on autotrophs, or primary producers, for the raw materials and fuel they need.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] Heterotrophs obtain energy by breaking down carbohydrates or oxidizing organic molecules (carbohydrates, fats, and proteins) obtained in food.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] Carnivorous organisms rely on autotrophs indirectly, as the nutrients obtained from their heterotrophic prey come from autotrophs they have consumed.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] Most ecosystems are supported by the autotrophic primary production of plants and cyanobacteria that capture photons initially released by the sun.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] Plants can only use a fraction (approximately 1%) of this energy for photosynthesis.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] The process of photosynthesis splits a water molecule (H2O), releasing oxygen (O2) into the atmosphere, and reducing carbon dioxide (CO2) to release hydrogen atoms that fuel the metabolic process of primary production.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] Plants convert and store the energy of the photons into the chemical bonds of simple sugars during photosynthesis.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] These plant sugars are polymerized for storage as long-chain carbohydrates, such as starch and cellulose; glucose is also used to make fats and proteins.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] When autotrophs are eaten by heterotrophs, i.e., consumers such as animals, the carbohydrates, fats, and proteins contained in them become energy sources for the heterotrophs.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] Proteins can be made using nitrates, sulfates, and phosphates in the soil.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] Aquatic algae are a significant contributor to food webs in tropical rivers and streams.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] This is displayed by net primary production, a fundamental ecological process that reflects the amount of carbon that is synthesized within an ecosystem.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] This carbon ultimately becomes available to consumers.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] Net primary production displays that the rates of in-stream primary production in tropical regions are at least an order of magnitude greater than in similar temperate systems.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] Researchers believe that the first cellular lifeforms were not heterotrophs as they would rely upon autotrophs since organic substrates delivered from space were either too heterogeneous to support microbial growth or too reduced to be fermented.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] Instead, they consider that the first cells were autotrophs.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] These autotrophs might have been thermophilic and anaerobic chemolithoautotrophs that lived at deep sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] This view is supported by phylogenetic evidence – the physiology and habitat of the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) is inferred to have also been a thermophilic anaerobe with a Wood-Ljungdahl pathway, its biochemistry was replete with FeS clusters and radical reaction mechanisms.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] The high concentration of K+ present within the cytosol of most life forms suggests that early cellular life had Na+/H+ antiporters or possibly symporters.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] Autotrophs possibly evolved into heterotrophs when they were at low H2 partial pressures where the first form of heterotrophy were likely amino acid and clostridial type purine fermentations.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] It has been suggested that photosynthesis emerged in the presence of faint near-infrared light emitted by hydrothermal vents.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] The first photochemically active pigments are then thought to be Zn-tetrapyrroles.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] The first autotrophic organisms likely evolved early in the Archean but proliferated across Earth's Great Oxidation Event with an increase to the rate of oxygenic photosynthesis by cyanobacteria.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] Photoautotrophs evolved from heterotrophic bacteria by developing photosynthesis.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] The earliest photosynthetic bacteria used hydrogen sulfide.
[src:auxotrophy/autotroph] Due to the scarcity of hydrogen sulfide, some photosynthetic bacteria evolved to use water in photosynthesis, leading to cyanobacteria.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] Prototrophic cells are self-sufficient producers of all required metabolites (e.g. amino acids, lipids, cofactors), while auxotrophs require to be on medium with the metabolite that they cannot produce.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] For example, a methionine auxotrophic cell could only grow on a medium that contained methionine; otherwise, it would starve.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] In this example, this is because it is unable to produce its own methionine.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] However, a methionine prototrophic cell would be able to function and replicate on a medium with or without methionine.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] Replica plating is a technique that transfers colonies from one plate to another in the same spot as the last plate so the different media plates can be compared side by side.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] It is used to compare the growth of the same colonies on different plates of media to determine which environments the bacterial colony can or cannot grow in (this gives insight to possible auxotrophic characteristics).
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] The method of replica plating implemented by Joshua Lederberg and Esther Lederberg included auxotrophs that were temperature-sensitive; that is, their ability to synthesize was temperature-dependent.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] (Auxotrophs are usually not temperature-dependent.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] They can also depend on other factors.) It is also possible that an organism is auxotrophic to more than just one organic compound that it requires for growth.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] In genetics, a strain is said to be auxotrophic if it carries a mutation that renders it unable to synthesize an essential compound.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] For example, a yeast mutant with an inactivated uracil synthesis pathway gene is a uracil auxotroph (e.g., if the yeast orotidine 5'-phosphate decarboxylase gene is inactivated, the resultant strain is a uracil auxotroph).
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] Such a strain is unable to synthesize uracil and will only be able to grow if uracil can be taken up from the environment.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] This is the opposite of a uracil prototroph, or in this case a wild-type strain, which can still grow in the absence of uracil.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] Auxotrophic genetic markers are often used in molecular genetics; they were famously used in Beadle and Tatum's Nobel Prize-winning work on the one gene-one enzyme hypothesis, connecting mutations of genes to protein mutations.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] This then allows for biosynthetic or biochemical pathway mapping that can help determine which enzyme or enzymes are mutated and dysfunctional in the auxotrophic strains of bacteria being studied.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] Researchers have used strains of *E. coli* auxotrophic for specific amino acids to introduce non-natural amino acid analogues into proteins.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] For instance cells auxotrophic for the amino acid phenylalanine can be grown in media supplemented with an analogue such as para-azido phenylalanine.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] Many living things, including humans, are auxotrophic for large classes of compounds required for growth and must obtain these compounds through diet (see vitamin, essential nutrient, essential amino acid, essential fatty acid).
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] The complex pattern of evolution of vitamin auxotrophy across the eukaryotic tree of life is intimately connected with the interdependence between organisms.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] The Salmonella Mutagenesis test (Ames test) uses multiple strains of *Salmonella typhimurium* that are auxotrophic to histidine to test whether a given chemical can cause mutations by observing its auxotrophic property in response to an added chemical compound.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] The mutation a chemical substance or compound causes is measured by applying it to the bacteria on a plate containing histidine then moving the bacteria to a new plate without sufficient histidine for continual growth.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] If the substance does not mutate the genome of the bacteria from auxotrophic to histidine back to prototrophic to histidine, then the bacteria would not show growth on the new plate.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] So by comparing the ratio of the bacteria on the new plate to the old plate and the same ratio for the control group, it is possible to quantify how mutagenic a substance is, or rather, how likely it is to cause mutations in DNA.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] A chemical is considered positive for Ames test if it causes mutations increasing the observed reversion rate and negative if presents similar to the control group.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] There is a normal, but small, number of revertant colonies expected when an auxotrophic bacteria is plated on a media without the metabolite it needs because it could mutate back to prototrophy.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] The chances of this are low and therefore cause very small colonies to be formed.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] If a mutagenic substance is added, however, the number of revertants would be visibly higher than without the mutagenic substance.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] The Ames test, basically, is considered positive if a substance increases chance of mutation in the DNA of the bacteria enough to cause a quantifiable difference in the revertants of the mutagen plate and the control group plate.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] Negative Ames test means the possible mutagen DID not cause increase in revertants and positive Ames test signifies that the possible mutagen DID increase the chance of mutation.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] These mutagenic effects on bacteria are researched as a possible indicator of the same effects on larger organisms, like humans.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] It is suggested that if a mutation can arise in bacterial DNA under presence of a mutagen then the same effect would occur for larger organisms causing cancer.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] A negative Ames test result could suggest that the substance is not a mutagen and would not cause tumor formation in living organisms.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] However only few of the positive Ames Test resulting chemicals were considered insignificant when tested in larger organisms but the positive Ames test for bacteria still could not be conclusively linked to expression of cancer in larger organisms.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] While it can be a possible determinant of tumors for living organisms, humans, animals, and so on, more studies must be completed to come to a conclusion.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] A large number of unnatural amino acids, which are similar to their canonical counterparts in shape, size and chemical properties, are introduced into the recombinant proteins by means of auxotrophic expression hosts.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] For example, methionine (Met) or tryptophan (Trp) auxotrophic *Escherichia coli* strains can be cultivated in a defined minimal medium.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] In this experimental setup it is possible to express recombinant proteins whose canonical Trp and Met residues are completely substituted with different medium-supplemented related analogs.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] This methodology leads to a new form of protein engineering, which is not performed by codon manipulation at the DNA level (e.g. oligonucleotide-directed mutagenesis), but by codon reassignments at the level of protein translation under efficient selective pressure.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] Therefore, the method is referred as selective pressure incorporation (SPI).
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] No organism studied so far encodes other amino acids than the canonical twenty; two additional canonical amino acids (selenocysteine, pyrrolysine) are inserted into proteins by recoding translation termination signals.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] This boundary can be crossed by adaptive laboratory evolution of metabolically stable auxotrophic microbial strains.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] For example, the first clearly successful attempt to evolve *Escherichia coli* that can survive solely on the unnatural amino acid thieno[3,2-b]pyrrolyl) alanine as the only substitute for tryptophan was made in 2015.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] The 1993 film *Jurassic Park* (based on the 1990 Michael Crichton novel of the same name) features dinosaurs that were genetically altered so that they could not produce the amino acid lysine.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] This was known as the "lysine contingency" and was supposed to prevent the cloned dinosaurs from surviving outside the park, forcing them to be dependent on lysine supplements provided by the park's veterinary staff.
[src:auxotrophy/auxotrophy] In reality, no animals are capable of producing lysine (it is an essential amino acid).
[src:auxotrophy/bradytroph] A **bradytroph** is a strain of an organism that exhibits slow growth in the absence of an external source of a particular metabolite.
[src:auxotrophy/bradytroph] This is usually due to a defect in an enzyme required in the metabolic pathway producing this chemical.
[src:auxotrophy/bradytroph] Such defects are the result of mutations in the genes encoding these enzymes.
[src:auxotrophy/bradytroph] As the organism can still produce small amounts of the chemical, the mutation is not lethal.
[src:auxotrophy/bradytroph] In these bradytroph strains, rapid growth occurs when the chemical is present in the cell's growth media and the missing metabolite can be transported into the cell from the external environment.
[src:auxotrophy/bradytroph] A bradytroph may also be referred to as a "leaky auxotroph".
[src:auxotrophy/bradytroph] The first usage of "bradytroph" was to describe *Escherichia coli* mutants partially defective in arginine biosynthesis.
[src:auxotrophy/bradytroph] Among many other examples of bradytrophic strains of microorganisms are *Bacillus subtilis* strains with mutations affecting thiamine production and *Saccharomyces cerevisiae* strains with mutations that impair arginine biosynthesis.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The artificial cloning of organisms, sometimes known as reproductive cloning, is often accomplished via somatic-cell nuclear transfer (SCNT), a cloning method in which a viable embryo is created from a somatic cell and an egg cell.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] In 1996, Dolly the sheep achieved notoriety for being the first mammal cloned from an adult somatic cell.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Another example of artificial cloning is molecular cloning, a technique in molecular biology in which a single living cell is used to clone a large population of cells that contain identical DNA molecules.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] In bioethics, there are a variety of ethical positions regarding the practice and possibilities of cloning.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The use of embryonic stem cells, which can be produced through SCNT, in some stem cell research has attracted controversy.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Cloning has been proposed as a means of reviving extinct species.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] In popular culture, the concept of cloning—particularly human cloning—is often depicted in science fiction; depictions commonly involve themes related to identity, the recreation of historical figures or extinct species, or cloning for exploitation (e.g. cloning soldiers for warfare).
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Webber in 1903, the term **clone** derives from the Ancient Greek word κλών (*klōn*), *twig*, which is the process whereby a new plant is created from a twig.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] In botany, the term ***lusus*** was used.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] In horticulture, the spelling *clon* was used until the early twentieth century; the final *e* came into use to indicate the vowel is a "long o" instead of a "short o".
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Since the term entered the popular lexicon in a more general context, the spelling *clone* has been used exclusively.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Natural cloning is the production of clones without the involvement of genetic engineering techniques or human intervention (i.e. artificial cloning).
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Natural cloning occurs through a variety of natural mechanisms, from single-celled organisms to complex multicellular organisms, and has allowed life forms to spread for hundreds of millions of years.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Versions of this reproduction method are used by plants, fungi, and bacteria, and is also the way that clonal colonies reproduce themselves.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Some of the mechanisms are explored and used in plants and animals are binary fission, budding, fragmentation, and parthenogenesis.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] It can also occur during some forms of asexual reproduction, when a single parent organism produces genetically identical offspring by itself.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Many plants are well known for natural cloning ability, including blueberry plants, Hazel trees, the Pando trees, the Kentucky coffeetree, *Myrica*, and the American sweetgum.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] It also occurs accidentally in the case of identical twins, which are formed when a fertilized egg splits, creating two or more embryos that carry identical DNA.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Molecular cloning refers to the process of making multiple molecules.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Cloning is commonly used to amplify DNA fragments containing whole genes, but it can also be used to amplify any DNA sequence such as promoters, non-coding sequences and randomly fragmented DNA.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] It is used in a wide array of biological experiments and practical applications ranging from genetic fingerprinting to large scale protein production.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Occasionally, the term cloning is misleadingly used to refer to the identification of the chromosomal location of a gene associated with a particular phenotype of interest, such as in positional cloning.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] In practice, localization of the gene to a chromosome or genomic region does not necessarily enable one to isolate or amplify the relevant genomic sequence.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] To amplify any DNA sequence in a living organism, that sequence must be linked to an origin of replication, which is a sequence of DNA capable of directing the propagation of itself and any linked sequence.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Although these steps are invariable among cloning procedures a number of alternative routes can be selected that do not use ligation.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Initially, the DNA of interest needs to be isolated to provide a DNA segment of suitable size.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Subsequently, a ligation procedure is used where the amplified fragment is inserted into a vector (piece of DNA).
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The vector (which is frequently circular) is linearised using restriction enzymes, and incubated with the fragment of interest under appropriate conditions with an enzyme called DNA ligase.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Although this restriction/ligation method is the traditional method, other methods that rely on recombination (such as Gibson assemblyor Golden Gate Cloning) have been developed and are commonly used.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] These do not use restriction enzymes but use overlaps between the insert and vector to cause recombination.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Whether restriction/ligation or another method is used, the vector with the insert of interest is transformed into cells.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] A number of alternative techniques are available, such as chemical sensitization of cells, electroporation, optical injection and biolistics.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Finally, the transfected cells are cultured, selecting for cells that had taken up the vector.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] As the aforementioned procedures are of particularly low efficiency, there is a need to identify the cells that have been successfully transfected with the vector construct containing the desired insertion sequence in the required orientation.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Modern cloning vectors include selectable antibiotic resistance markers, which allow only cells in which the vector has successfully transformed, to grow.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Additionally, the cloning vectors may contain colour selection markers, which provide blue/white screening (alpha-factor complementation) on X-gal medium.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Nevertheless, these selection steps do not absolutely guarantee that the DNA insert is present in the cells obtained.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Further investigation of the resulting colonies must be required to confirm that cloning was successful.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] This may be accomplished by means of PCR, restriction fragment analysis and/or DNA sequencing.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Cloning a cell means to derive a population of cells from a single cell.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] In the case of unicellular organisms such as bacteria and yeast, this process is remarkably simple and essentially only requires the inoculation of the appropriate medium.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] However, in the case of cell cultures from multi-cellular organisms, cell cloning is an arduous task as these cells will not readily grow in standard media.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] A useful tissue culture technique used to clone distinct lineages of cell lines involves the use of cloning rings (cylinders).
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] In this technique a single-cell suspension of cells that have been exposed to a mutagenic agent or drug used to drive selection is plated at high dilution to create isolated colonies, each arising from a single and potentially clonal distinct cell.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] At an early growth stage when colonies consist of only a few cells, sterile polystyrene rings (cloning rings), which have been dipped in grease, are placed over an individual colony and a small amount of trypsin is added.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Cloned cells are collected from inside the ring and transferred to a new vessel for further growth.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Somatic-cell nuclear transfer, popularly known as SCNT, can also be used to create embryos for research or therapeutic purposes.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The most likely purpose for this is to produce embryos for use in stem cell research.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] This process is also called "research cloning" or "therapeutic cloning".
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The goal is not to create cloned human beings (called "reproductive cloning"), but rather to harvest stem cells that can be used to study human development and to potentially treat disease.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] While a clonal human blastocyst has been created, stem cell lines are yet to be isolated from a clonal source.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Therapeutic cloning is achieved by creating embryonic stem cells in the hopes of treating diseases such as diabetes and Alzheimer's.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The process begins by removing the nucleus (containing the DNA) from an egg cell and inserting a nucleus from the adult cell to be cloned.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] In the case of someone with Alzheimer's disease, the nucleus from a skin cell of that patient is placed into an empty egg.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The reprogrammed cell begins to develop into an embryo because the egg reacts with the transferred nucleus.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The embryo will become genetically identical to the patient.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The embryo will then form a blastocyst which has the potential to form/become any cell in the body.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The reason why SCNT is used for cloning is because somatic cells can be easily acquired and cultured in the lab.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] This process can either add or delete specific genomes of farm animals.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] A key point to remember is that cloning is achieved when the oocyte maintains its normal functions and instead of using sperm and egg genomes to replicate, the donor's somatic cell nucleus is inserted into the oocyte.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The oocyte will react to the somatic cell nucleus, the same way it would to a sperm cell's nucleus.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The process of cloning a particular farm animal using SCNT is relatively the same for all animals.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The first step is to collect the somatic cells from the animal that will be cloned.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The somatic cells could be used immediately or stored in the laboratory for later use.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The hardest part of SCNT is removing maternal DNA from an oocyte at metaphase II.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Once this has been done, the somatic nucleus can be inserted into an egg cytoplasm.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The grouped somatic cell and egg cytoplasm are then introduced to an electrical current.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] This energy will hopefully allow the cloned embryo to begin development.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The successfully developed embryos are then placed in surrogate recipients, such as a cow or sheep in the case of farm animals.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] SCNT is seen as a good method for producing agriculture animals for food consumption.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] It successfully cloned sheep, cattle, goats, and pigs.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Another benefit is SCNT is seen as a solution to clone endangered species that are on the verge of going extinct.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] However, stresses placed on both the egg cell and the introduced nucleus can be enormous, which led to a high loss in resulting cells in early research.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] For example, the cloned sheep Dolly was born after 277 eggs were used for SCNT, which created 29 viable embryos.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Only three of these embryos survived until birth, and only one survived to adulthood.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] As the procedure could not be automated, and had to be performed manually under a microscope, SCNT was very resource intensive.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The biochemistry involved in reprogramming the differentiated somatic cell nucleus and activating the recipient egg was also far from being well understood.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] However, by 2014 researchers were reporting cloning success rates of seven to eight out of ten and in 2016, a Korean Company Sooam Biotech was reported to be producing 500 cloned embryos per day.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] In SCNT, not all of the donor cell's genetic information is transferred, as the donor cell's mitochondria that contain their own mitochondrial DNA are left behind.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The resulting hybrid cells retain those mitochondrial structures which originally belonged to the egg.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] As a consequence, clones such as Dolly that are born from SCNT are not perfect copies of the donor of the nucleus.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The term *clone* is used in horticulture to refer to descendants of a single plant which were produced by vegetative reproduction or apomixis.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Many horticultural plant cultivars are clones, having been derived from a single individual, multiplied by some process other than sexual reproduction.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] As an example, some European cultivars of grapes represent clones that have been propagated for over two millennia.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Other examples are potatoes and bananas.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Grafting can be regarded as cloning, since all the shoots and branches coming from the graft are genetically a clone of a single individual, but this particular kind of cloning has not come under ethical scrutiny and is generally treated as an entirely different kind of operation.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Many trees, shrubs, vines, ferns and other herbaceous perennials form clonal colonies naturally.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Parts of an individual plant may become detached by fragmentation and grow on to become separate clonal individuals.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] A common example is in the vegetative reproduction of moss and liverwort gametophyte clones by means of gemmae.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Some vascular plants e.g. dandelion and certain viviparous grasses also form seeds asexually, termed apomixis, resulting in clonal populations of genetically identical individuals.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Clonal derivation exists in nature in some animal species and is referred to as parthenogenesis (reproduction of an organism by itself without a mate).
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] This is an asexual form of reproduction that is only found in females of some insects, crustaceans, nematodes, fish (for example the hammerhead shark), Cape honeybees, and lizards including the Komodo dragon and several whiptails.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The growth and development occurs without fertilization by a male.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] In plants, parthenogenesis means the development of an embryo from an unfertilized egg cell, and is a component process of apomixis.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] In species that use the XY sex-determination system, the offspring will always be female.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] An example of partenogenesis is the little fire ant (*Wasmannia auropunctata*), which is native to Central and South America but has spread throughout many tropical environments.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Artificial cloning of organisms may also be called *reproductive cloning*.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Hans Spemann, a German embryologist was awarded a Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1935 for his discovery of the effect now known as embryonic induction, exercised by various parts of the embryo, that directs the development of groups of cells into particular tissues and organs.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] In 1924 he and his student, Hilde Mangold, were the first to perform somatic-cell nuclear transfer using amphibian embryos – one of the first steps towards cloning.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Reproductive cloning generally uses "somatic cell nuclear transfer" (SCNT) to create animals that are genetically identical.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] This process entails the transfer of a nucleus from a donor adult cell (somatic cell) to an egg from which the nucleus has been removed, or to a cell from a blastocyst from which the nucleus has been removed.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] If the egg begins to divide normally it is transferred into the uterus of the surrogate mother.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Such clones are not strictly identical since the somatic cells may contain mutations in their nuclear DNA.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Additionally, the mitochondria in the cytoplasm also contains DNA and during SCNT this mitochondrial DNA is wholly from the cytoplasmic donor's egg, thus the mitochondrial genome is not the same as that of the nucleus donor cell from which it was produced.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] This may have important implications for cross-species nuclear transfer in which nuclear-mitochondrial incompatibilities may lead to death.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Artificial *embryo splitting* or *embryo twinning*, a technique that creates monozygotic twins from a single embryo, is not considered in the same fashion as other methods of cloning.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] During that procedure, a donor embryo is split in two distinct embryos, that can then be transferred via embryo transfer.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] It is optimally performed at the 6- to 8-cell stage, where it can be used as an expansion of IVF to increase the number of available embryos.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] If both embryos are successful, it gives rise to monozygotic (identical) twins.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Dolly, a Finn-Dorset ewe, was the first mammal to have been successfully cloned from an adult somatic cell.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Dolly was formed by taking a cell from the udder of her 6-year-old biological mother.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Contrary to popular belief, she was not the first animal to be cloned.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Dolly's embryo was created by taking the cell and inserting it into a sheep ovum.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] It took 435 attempts before an embryo was successful.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The embryo was then placed inside a female sheep that went through a normal pregnancy.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] She was cloned at the Roslin Institute in Scotland by British scientists Sir Ian Wilmut and Keith Campbell and lived there from her birth in 1996 until her death in 2003 when she was six.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] She was born on 5 July 1996 but not announced to the world until 22 February 1997.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Her stuffed remains were placed at Edinburgh's Royal Museum, part of the National Museums of Scotland.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Dolly was publicly significant because the effort showed that genetic material from a specific adult cell, designed to express only a distinct subset of its genes, can be redesigned to grow an entirely new organism.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Before this demonstration, it had been shown by John Gurdon that nuclei from differentiated cells could give rise to an entire organism after transplantation into an enucleated egg.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] However, this concept was not yet demonstrated in a mammalian system.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The first mammalian cloning (resulting in Dolly) had a success rate of 29 embryos per 277 fertilized eggs, which produced three lambs at birth, one of which lived.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] In a bovine experiment involving 70 cloned calves, one-third of the calves died quite young.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The first successfully cloned horse, Prometea, took 814 attempts.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Notably, although the first clones were frogs, no adult cloned frog has yet been produced from a somatic adult nucleus donor cell.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] There were early claims that Dolly had pathologies resembling accelerated aging.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Scientists speculated that Dolly's death in 2003 was related to the shortening of telomeres, DNA-protein complexes that protect the end of linear chromosomes.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] However, other researchers, including Ian Wilmut who led the team that successfully cloned Dolly, argue that Dolly's early death due to respiratory infection was unrelated to problems with the cloning process.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] This idea that the nuclei have not irreversibly aged was shown in 2013 to be true for mice.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Dolly was named after performer Dolly Parton because the cells cloned to make her were from a mammary gland cell, and Parton is known for her ample cleavage.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] In 2024, Colossal Biosciences announced they had brought the dire wolf back from extinction via cloning and genetic engineering.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The biotech company created three grey wolf clones with 14 genes edited to express traits likely similar to those of dire wolves.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Many scientists have contested whether the clones can be considered true dire wolves.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The modern cloning techniques involving nuclear transfer have been successfully performed on several species.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Human cloning is the creation of a genetically identical copy of a human.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The term is generally used to refer to artificial human cloning, which is the reproduction of human cells and tissues.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] It does not refer to the natural conception and delivery of identical twins.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The possibility of human cloning has raised controversies.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] These ethical concerns have prompted several nations to pass legislation regarding human cloning and its legality.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] In 2018, scientists declared they had no intention of trying to clone people, and they believed their results should spark a wider discussion about the laws and regulations the world needs to regulate cloning.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Two commonly discussed types of theoretical human cloning are *therapeutic cloning* and *reproductive cloning*.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Therapeutic cloning would involve cloning cells from a human for use in medicine and transplants, and is an active area of research, but is not in medical practice anywhere in the world, as of 2024.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Two common methods of therapeutic cloning that are being researched are somatic-cell nuclear transfer and, more recently, pluripotent stem cell induction.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Reproductive cloning would involve making an entire cloned human, instead of just specific cells or tissues.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] There are a variety of ethical positions regarding the possibilities of cloning, especially human cloning.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] While many of these views are religious in origin, the questions raised by cloning are faced by secular perspectives as well.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Perspectives on human cloning are theoretical, as human therapeutic and reproductive cloning are not commercially used; animals are currently cloned in laboratories and in livestock production.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Advocates support development of therapeutic cloning to generate tissues and whole organs to treat patients who otherwise cannot obtain transplants, to avoid the need for immunosuppressive drugs, and to stave off the effects of aging.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Advocates for reproductive cloning believe that parents who cannot otherwise procreate should have access to the technology.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Cloning humans could lead to serious violations of human rights.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Religious groups are divided, with some opposing the technology as usurping "God's place" and, to the extent embryos are used, destroying a human life; others support therapeutic cloning's potential life-saving benefits.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] There is at least one religion, Raëlism, in which cloning plays a major role.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Contemporary work on this topic is concerned with the ethics, adequate regulation and issues of any cloning carried out by humans, not potentially by extraterrestrials (including in the future), and largely also not replication – also described as mind cloning – of potential whole brain emulations.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Cloning of animals is opposed by animal-groups due to the number of cloned animals that suffer from malformations before they die, and while food from cloned animals has been approved as safe by the US FDA, its use is opposed by groups concerned about food safety.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Cloning, or more precisely, the reconstruction of functional DNA from extinct species has, for decades, been a dream.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Possible implications of this were dramatized in the 1984 novel *Carnosaur* and the 1990 novel *Jurassic Park*.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The best current cloning techniques have an average success rate of 9.4 percent (and as high as 25 percent) when working with familiar species such as mice, while cloning wild animals is usually less than 1 percent successful.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Several tissue banks have come into existence, including the "Frozen zoo" at the San Diego Zoo, to store frozen tissue from the world's rarest and most endangered species.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] This is also referred to as "Conservation cloning".
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Engineers have proposed a "lunar ark" in 2021 – storing millions of seed, spore, sperm and egg samples from Earth's contemporary species in a network of lava tubes on the Moon as a genetic backup.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Similar proposals have been made since at least 2008.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] These also include sending human customer DNA, and a proposal for "a lunar backup record of humanity" that includes genetic information by Avi Loeb et al.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] In 2020, the San Diego Zoo began a number of projects in partnership with the conservation organization Revive & Restore and the ViaGen Pets and Equine Company to clone individuals of genetically-impoverished endangered species.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] A Przewalski's horse was cloned from preserved tissue of a stallion whose genes are absent in the surviving populations of the species, which descend from twenty individuals.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The clone, named Kurt, had been born to a domestic surrogate mother, and was partnered with a natural-born Przewalski's mare in order to socialize him with the species' natural behavior before being introduced to the Zoo's breeding herd.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] In 2023, a second clone of the original stallion, named Ollie, was born; this marked the first instance of multiple living clones of a single individual of an endangered species being alive at the same time.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Also in 2020, a clone named Elizabeth Ann was produced of a female black-footed ferret that had no living descendants.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] While Elizabeth Ann became sterile due to secondary health complications, a pair of additional clones of the same individual, named Antonia and Noreen, were born to distinct surrogate mothers, and Antonia successfully reproduced later in the year.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] One of the most anticipated targets for cloning was once the woolly mammoth, but attempts to extract DNA from frozen mammoths have been unsuccessful, though a joint Russo-Japanese team is currently working toward this goal.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] In January 2011, it was reported by Yomiuri Shimbun that a team of scientists headed by Akira Iritani of Kyoto University had built upon research by Dr.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Wakayama, saying that they will extract DNA from a mammoth carcass that had been preserved in a Russian laboratory and insert it into the egg cells of an Asian elephant in hopes of producing a mammoth embryo.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The researchers said they hoped to produce a baby mammoth within six years.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Extensively degraded DNA that may be suitable for sequencing may not be suitable for cloning; it would have to be synthetically reconstituted.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] In any case, with currently available technology, DNA alone is not suitable for mammalian cloning; intact viable cell nuclei are required.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Patching pieces of reconstituted mammoth DNA into an Asian elephant cell nucleus would result in an elephant-mammoth hybrid rather than a true mammoth.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Moreover, true de-extinction of the wooly mammoth species would require a breeding population, which would require cloning of multiple genetically distinct but reproductively compatible individuals, multiplying both the amount of work and the uncertainties involved in the project.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] There are potentially other post-cloning problems associated with the survival of a reconstructed mammoth, such as the requirement of ruminants for specific symbiotic microbiota in their stomachs for digestion.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Scientists at the University of Newcastle and University of New South Wales announced in March 2013 that the very recently extinct gastric-brooding frog would be the subject of a cloning attempt to resurrect the species.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Many such "de-extinction" projects are being championed by the non-profit Revive & Restore.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] In 2022, scientists showed major limitations and the scale of challenge of genetic-editing-based de-extinction, suggesting resources spent on more comprehensive de-extinction projects such as of the woolly mammoth may currently not be well allocated and substantially limited.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] In a 2021 online session of the Russian Geographical Society, Russia's defense minister Sergei Shoigu mentioned using the DNA of 3,000-year-old Scythian warriors to potentially bring them back to life.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The idea was described as absurd at least at this point in news reports and it was noted that Scythians likely weren't skilled warriors by default.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The idea of cloning Neanderthals or bringing them back to life in general is controversial but some scientists have stated that it may be possible in the future and have outlined several issues or problems with such as well as broad rationales for doing so.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] In 2001, a cow named Bessie gave birth to a cloned Asian gaur, an endangered species, but the calf died after two days.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] In 2003, a banteng was successfully cloned, followed by three African wildcats from a thawed frozen embryo.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] These successes provided hope that similar techniques (using surrogate mothers of another species) might be used to clone extinct species.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Anticipating this possibility, tissue samples from the last *bucardo* (Pyrenean ibex) were frozen in liquid nitrogen immediately after it died in 2000.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Researchers are also considering cloning endangered species such as the Giant panda and Cheetah.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] In 2002, geneticists at the Australian Museum announced that they had replicated DNA of the thylacine (Tasmanian tiger), at the time extinct for about 65 years, using polymerase chain reaction.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] However, on 15 February 2005 the museum announced that it was stopping the project after tests showed the specimens' DNA had been too badly degraded by the (ethanol) preservative.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] On 15 May 2005 it was announced that the thylacine project would be revived, with new participation from researchers in New South Wales and Victoria.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] In 2003, for the first time, an extinct animal, the Pyrenean ibex mentioned above was cloned, at the Centre of Food Technology and Research of Aragon, using the preserved frozen cell nucleus of the skin samples from 2001 and domestic goat egg-cells.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] The ibex died shortly after birth due to physical defects in its lungs.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] After an eight-year project involving the use of a pioneering cloning technique, Japanese researchers created 25 generations of healthy cloned mice with normal lifespans, demonstrating that clones are not intrinsically shorter-lived than naturally born animals.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Other sources have noted that the offspring of clones tend to be healthier than the original clones and indistinguishable from animals produced naturally.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Some posited that Dolly the sheep may have aged more quickly than naturally born animals, as she died relatively early for a sheep at the age of six.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Ultimately, her death was attributed to a respiratory illness, and the "advanced aging" theory is disputed.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] A 2016 study indicated that once cloned animals survive the first month or two of life they are generally healthy.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] However, early pregnancy loss and neonatal losses are still greater with cloning than natural conception or assisted reproduction (IVF).
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p01] Current research is attempting to overcome these problems.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] Discussion of cloning in the popular media often presents the subject negatively.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] In an article in the 8 November 1993 article of *Time*, cloning was portrayed in a negative way, modifying Michelangelo's *Creation of Adam* to depict Adam with five identical hands.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] *Newsweek*'s 10 March 1997 issue also critiqued the ethics of human cloning, and included a graphic depicting identical babies in beakers.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] The concept of cloning, particularly human cloning, has featured a wide variety of science fiction works.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] An early fictional depiction of cloning is Bokanovsky's Process which features in Aldous Huxley's 1931 dystopian novel *Brave New World*.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] The process is applied to fertilized human eggs *in vitro*, causing them to split into identical genetic copies of the original.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] Following renewed interest in cloning in the 1950s, the subject was explored further in works such as Poul Anderson's 1953 story *UN-Man*, which describes a technology called "exogenesis", and Gordon Rattray Taylor's book *The Biological Time Bomb*, which popularised the term "cloning" in 1963.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] The process of cloning is represented variously in fiction.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] Many works depict the artificial creation of humans by a method of growing cells from a tissue or DNA sample; the replication may be instantaneous, or take place through slow growth of human embryos in artificial wombs.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] The clones in this story are short-lived, and can only survive a matter of minutes before they expire.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] Science fiction films such as *The Matrix* and *Star Wars: Episode II – Attack of the Clones* have featured scenes of human foetuses being cultured on an industrial scale in mechanical tanks.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] Cloning humans from body parts is also a common theme in science fiction.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] Cloning features strongly among the science fiction conventions parodied in Woody Allen's *Sleeper*, the plot of which centres around an attempt to clone an assassinated dictator from his disembodied nose.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] In the 2008 *Doctor Who* story "Journey's End", a duplicate version of the Tenth Doctor spontaneously grows from his severed hand, which had been cut off in a sword fight during an earlier episode.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] After the death of her beloved 14-year-old Coton de Tulear named Samantha in late 2017, Barbra Streisand announced that she had cloned the dog, and was now "waiting for [the two cloned pups] to get older so [she] can see if they have [Samantha's] brown eyes and her seriousness".
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] The operation cost $50,000 through the pet cloning company ViaGen.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] In films such as Roger Spottiswoode's 2000 *The 6th Day*, which makes use of the trope of a "vast clandestine laboratory ... filled with row upon row of 'blank' human bodies kept floating in tanks of nutrient liquid or in suspended animation", clearly fear is to be incited.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] In Clark's view, the biotechnology is typically "given fantastic but visually arresting forms" while the science is either relegated to the background or fictionalised to suit a young audience.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] In November 2025, former American football quarterback Tom Brady received a lot of criticism when he announced that his dog Junie is a clone of his late dog Lua.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] Science fiction has used cloning, most commonly and specifically human cloning, to address questions of identity and eugenics.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] *A Number* is a 2002 play by English playwright Caryl Churchill which addresses the subject of human cloning and identity, especially nature and nurture.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] The story, set in the near future, is structured around the conflict between a father (Salter) and his sons (Bernard 1, Bernard 2, and Michael Black) –the second two of whom are clones of the first.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] *A Number* was adapted by Caryl Churchill for television, in a co-production between the BBC and HBO Films.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] In 2012, a Japanese television series named "Bunshin" was created.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] The story's main character, Mariko, is a woman studying child welfare in Hokkaido.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] She grew up always doubtful about the love from her mother, who looked nothing like her and who died nine years before.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] One day, she finds some of her mother's belongings at a relative's house, and heads to Tokyo to seek out the truth behind her birth.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] She later discovered that she was a clone.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] In the 2013 television series *Orphan Black*, cloning is used as a scientific study on the behavioral adaptation of the clones.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] In a similar vein, the book *The Double* by Nobel Prize winner José Saramago explores the emotional experience of a man who discovers that he is a clone.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] Cloning has been used in fiction as a way of recreating historical figures.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] In the 1976 Ira Levin novel *The Boys from Brazil* and its 1978 film adaptation, Josef Mengele uses cloning to create copies of Adolf Hitler.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] The Norman Spinrad's satirical *The Iron Dream*, published in 1972, concludes with 300 seven-foot-tall, blond, super-intelligent all-male SS clones in suspended animation launched into space to begin the Hitler analog's galactic empire in the aftermath of a genocidal race war.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] (They had won a Pyrrhic victory, the subhumans' leader having as his last act detonated a doomsday weapon, specifically a cobalt bomb, irredeemably contaminated the gene pool).
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] In Michael Crichton's 1990 novel *Jurassic Park*, which spawned a series of *Jurassic Park* feature films, the bioengineering company InGen develops a technique to resurrect extinct species of dinosaurs by creating cloned creatures using DNA extracted from fossils.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] The cloned dinosaurs are used to populate the Jurassic Park wildlife park for the entertainment of visitors.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] The scheme goes disastrously wrong when the dinosaurs escape their enclosures.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] The use of cloning for military purposes has also been explored in several fictional works.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] In *Doctor Who*, an alien race of armour-clad, warlike beings called Sontarans was introduced in the 1973 serial "The Time Warrior".
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] Sontarans are depicted as squat, bald creatures who have been genetically engineered for combat.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] Their weak spot is a "probic vent", a small socket at the back of their neck which is associated with the cloning process.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] The concept of cloned soldiers being bred for combat was revisited in "The Doctor's Daughter" (2008), when the Doctor's DNA is used to create a female warrior called Jenny.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] The 1977 film *Star Wars* was set against the backdrop of a historical conflict called the Clone Wars.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] The events of this war were not fully explored until the prequel films *Attack of the Clones* (2002) and *Revenge of the Sith* (2005), which depict a space war waged by a massive army of heavily armoured clone troopers that leads to the foundation of the Galactic Empire.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] Cloned soldiers are "manufactured" on an industrial scale, genetically conditioned for obedience and combat effectiveness.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] It is also revealed that the popular character Boba Fett originated as a clone of Jango Fett, a mercenary who served as the genetic template for the clone troopers.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] A recurring sub-theme of cloning fiction is the use of clones as a supply of organs for transplantation.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] The 2005 Kazuo Ishiguro novel *Never Let Me Go* and the 2010 film adaption are set in an alternate history in which cloned humans are created for the sole purpose of providing organ donations to naturally born humans, despite the fact that they are fully sentient and self-aware.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] The 2005 film *The Island* revolves around a similar plot, with the exception that the clones are unaware of the reason for their existence.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] The exploitation of human clones for dangerous and undesirable work was examined in the 2009 British science fiction film *Moon*.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] In the futuristic novel *Cloud Atlas* and subsequent film, one of the story lines focuses on a genetically engineered fabricant clone named Sonmi~451, one of millions raised in an artificial "wombtank", destined to serve from birth.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] She is one of thousands created for manual and emotional labor; Sonmi herself works as a server in a restaurant.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] She later discovers that the sole source of food for clones, called 'Soap', is manufactured from the clones themselves.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] In the film *Us*, at some point prior to the 1980s, the US Government creates clones of every citizen of the United States with the intention of using them to control their original counterparts, akin to voodoo dolls.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] This fails, as they were able to copy bodies, but unable to copy the souls of those they cloned.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] The project is abandoned and the clones are trapped exactly mirroring their above-ground counterparts' actions for generations.
[src:auxotrophy/cloning-p02] In the present day, the clones launch a surprise attack and manage to complete a mass-genocide of their unaware counterparts.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] Proteins are essential to life, performing many necessary cellular functions.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] Cells construct proteins with amino acids using DNA instructions.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] Typically, DNA is transcribed into messenger RNA (mRNA) and the mRNA is translated into a sequence of amino acids.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] The complex that facilitates translation from mRNA to amino acid is called the ribosome.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] Ribosomes hold and read mRNA in three nucleotide chunks called codons.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] Codons have a corresponding transport RNA (tRNA) that binds to the ribosome. tRNAs are responsible for bringing amino acids to the ribosome so they can be incorporated into the protein.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] Though each codon only codes for a single tRNA, a tRNA can represent multiple codons.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] This is because there are 64 possible codon combinations and 20 natural amino acids.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] Each tRNA codes for a single amino acid.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] Each amino acid is added to the growing chain of amino acids that will form the final protein.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] The initial chain of amino acids, also called the primary structure of the protein, determines the final shape and functional capacity of the protein.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] When codon reassignment occurs, it is usually due to a change in tRNAs.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] A tRNA can be assigned to a new codon or the tRNA can be altered to pick up a different amino acid.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] For the protein, this means either swapping one amino acid for another, or in the case of a stop codon, adding an amino acid where there was none before.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] Since the primary structure determines the functionality of a protein, changing even one amino acid in this way can drastically impact what the final protein is able to do.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] In bacteria and yeast, codon reassignment can be caused by a shortage of required amino acids.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] Instead of halting protein production all together, tRNA molecules select another amino acid to add to the amino acid chain.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] This amino acid may have similar properties to the intended amino acid, or it may not.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] This may cause deformities in the proteins, making them less efficient or even nonfunctional.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] A hypothesis as to why this phenomenon persists despite the loss of efficiency is that it is preferable for the organism to have a worse version of the protein than to have no protein at all.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] In some human cancer cells, such as melanoma cells, a similar tactic is used.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] As an immune response, to try and destroy the cancer, T cells release an enzyme that destroys the essential amino acid tryptophan within the cancer cells.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] This typically deprives the cancer of many key proteins, killing the cancer cells.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] However, some cancer cells are able to use codon reassignment to replace the tryptophan with a similar amino acid called phenylalanine.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] This amino acid replacement and resulting functional protein allows the cancer cell to survive and continue dividing.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] In some bacteriophages, tRNAs have been assigned to stop codons TAG and TGA to code for amino acids glutamine and tryptophan respectively.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] The reasons for this codon reassignment are still being studied, it may be related to the infection process.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] Exposure to outside environmental factors can alter tRNA molecules enough to result in codon reassignment.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] For example, after being infected with a certain virus, rat liver cells can replace the amino acid selenocysteine with cysteine, a structurally similar amino acid.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] It has been well documented that there are variations in genetic code within between nucleic DNA, mitochondrial DNA and chloroplast DNA.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] However, it was previously thought that the genetic code was consistent across species within the nucleus.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] The existence of codon reassignment challenges this idea.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] The same codon may code for different amino acids in different species.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] Codon reassignment shows flexibility and adaptability within genetic code.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] Artificial, synthetic, unnatural, or non-proteinogenic amino acids are used in research to help understand the construction and functionality of proteins.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] These artificial amino acids are also used in some medications.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] Researchers normally use stop codons, which do not code for an amino acid, to insert these amino acids into proteins.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] Since there are only three stop codons, researchers were previously limited to using only one or two artificial amino acids.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] There was also an option to use artificial tRNA molecules to insert artificial amino acids, but these artificial tRNA molecules are not as high quality as natural tRNA molecules, often making mistakes.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] The ability to reassign natural tRNA to artificial amino acids through codon reassignment unlocks many possibilities for this research.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] Since there are 64 possible combinations and only about 20 natural amino acids, this method would allow researchers to hypothetically insert 43 artificial amino acids into a protein, preserving one stop codon to complete the translation process properly.
[src:auxotrophy/codon-reassignment] These advancements in genetic and protein manipulation may help scientists and doctors to deepen humanity's understanding of cellular functions and produce more effective and efficient medicines.
